Configure Links in Linux
------------------------

We will configure links in Linux.
There are two types of links in Linux:

Hard Link:
Points directly to the data on disk. Multiple hard links share the same inode. If the original file is deleted, the data remains accessible through other hard links.

Symbolic Link (Soft Link):
A shortcut that points to another file or directory by path. If the original file is deleted, the symbolic link becomes broken.

Steps:
Create two directories named /RealData and /DataLink
mkdir /RealData
mkdir /DataLink

Create a file named file1 in /RealData and add text:
"This line entered via the /RealData path"
nano /RealData/file1

Create a hard link named fileA in /DataLink linked to file1 in /RealData
ln /RealData/file1 /DataLink/fileA

Edit /DataLink/fileA and add text:
"This line entered via the /DataLink path."
nano /DataLink/fileA


Create symbolic link
In your home directory, create a symbolic link named sym-fileA pointing to /DataLink/fileA:
ln -s /DataLink/fileA sym-fileA

Edit the file using the symbolic link: This line entered via the sym-fileA path
nano sym-fileA

Delete the file in /DataLink and check the symbolic link
Delete /DataLink/fileA:
rm -f /DataLink/fileA 
or
rm /DataLink/fileA

when we try to cat the symbolic link it will give an error
cat sym-fileA
*error

Find broken symbolic links:


Search the /var directory for symbolic links and their destinations:
